-- Ringgit Climbs Most in Six Weeks as U.S. Data Ease Fed Concern
-- B y   L i a u   Y - S i n g
-- 2013-08-05T08:32:09Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-08-05/ringgit-gains-most-in-a-month-as-u-s-jobs-data-ease-fed-concern.html
Malaysia’s ringgit strengthened the
most in six weeks after U.S. jobs data tempered speculation the
 Federal Reserve  is set to rein in stimulus that has boosted
demand for emerging-market assets.  Government bonds  climbed.  Payrolls in the world’s largest economy rose by 162,000 in
July, the least in four months, and below the 185,000 increase
forecast by economists. The Fed, which last week pledged to keep
buying $85 billion of bonds every month, said July 17 it may
even increase the quantitative easing if the economy doesn’t
perform to its expectations. Services industries in China,
Malaysia’s second-biggest market, showed the first pick-up in
growth since March, according to an Aug. 3 report.  “The payroll numbers were lower than expected and that has
pushed back expectations a bit that the Fed will start QE
tapering in September,” said Choong Yin Pheng, a senior manager
for fixed income and economic research at Hong Leong Bank Bhd.
in  Kuala Lumpur . “For this week, the ringgit will trade in the
range of 3.22-3.28.”  The currency strengthened 0.9 percent, the most since June
25, to 3.2280 per dollar as of 4:22 p.m. in Kuala Lumpur,
according to data compiled by Bloomberg. It touched 3.2590 on
Aug. 2, the weakest level since July 2010. One-month implied
volatility, a measure of expected moves in exchange rates used
to price options, fell 35 basis points to 8.38 percent.  China’s non-manufacturing  Purchasing Managers ’ Index rose
to 54.1 in July from 53.9 in June, the National Bureau of
Statistics and China Federation of Logistics and Purchasing
said. A report compiled by Markit released today showed China’s
services activity was unchanged in July.  Exports Slip  Malaysian  exports  fell 6.9 percent in June, the fifth
straight month of declines, according to official figures
released today. Imports grew 1.3 percent and the  trade surplus 
widened to 4.32 billion ringgit from 2.88 billion ringgit n May.
The nation’s  current account , the broadest measure of trade,
dropped 62 percent in the first quarter to 8.7 billion ringgit,
official data show.  “The trade balance data has somewhat alleviated fears that
the current account is under threat, at least for now,” said
 Gundy Cahyadi , an economist at Oversea-Chinese Banking Corp. in
 Singapore . “That could play in the minds of investors as
well.”  The yield on the 3.26 percent sovereign notes due March
2018 retreated five basis points, or 0.05 percentage point, to
3.67 percent, according to data compiled by Bloomberg.  To contact the reporter on this story:
